  <li><strong>Assess Oak Integration Carefully</strong> - When reviewing oaked Sauvignon Blanc, evaluate whether the wood enhances or masks the varietal character. Premium examples from Pessac-Léognan show seamless integration where vanilla and spice complement rather than overwhelm the citrus and herbaceous core. Poorly integrated oak creates a disjointed wine that loses Sauvignon Blanc's essential vibrancy.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Time Your Tasting to Vintage Character</strong> - Most Sauvignon Blancs peak within 18 months of vintage, but premium examples from Sancerre, Pouilly-Fumé, or Marlborough's top sites can develop for 3-5 years. Review young wines for primary fruit intensity, but aged examples for how well they've maintained freshness while developing honeyed complexity and mineral depth.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Evaluate Botrytis Influence in Sweet Styles</strong> - When reviewing dessert-style Sauvignon Blancs, assess how noble rot has transformed the grape's natural acidity and aromatics. Premium examples from Sauternes or New Zealand show concentrated honey and dried fruit flavors while maintaining Sauvignon Blanc's characteristic acidity structure, creating wines with decades of aging potential.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Consider Lees Contact Duration Effects</strong> - Identify whether the wine spent time on fine lees by tasting for increased textural weight and subtle biscuity notes. Extended lees contact (3-6 months) adds complexity and aging potential to premium Sauvignon Blancs, particularly in cooler climate expressions, while maintaining the variety's essential freshness and aromatic precision.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Our comprehensive Sauvignon Blanc review revealed surprising variations in aging potential across different styles and regions. While most food writers dismiss Sauvignon Blanc as strictly early-drinking, our tastings proved this generalization wrong.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Style</h3>

<p><strong>Loire Valley Sancerre and Pouilly-Fumé</strong> showed remarkable longevity, with top producers like Henri Bourgeois and Didier Dagueneau developing beautifully over 8-12 years. The mineral-driven terroir and higher acidity create a backbone for extended aging.</p>

<p><strong>Premium Bordeaux Blanc</strong> blends (typically Sauvignon Blanc with Sémillon) from producers like Domaine de Chevalier aged gracefully for 10-15 years, developing honeyed complexity while retaining freshness.</p>

<p><strong>New World expressions</strong> varied dramatically. Top New Zealand examples from Marlborough's Wairau Valley showed 5-7 year potential, while most Australian and South African bottlings peaked within 2-3 years.</p>

<h3>Evolution Over Time</h3>

<p>Well-aged Sauvignon Blanc transforms from bright citrus and herbaceous notes toward <strong>developed aromatics</strong>: wet stone minerality, lanolin texture, and subtle honeyed fruit. The aggressive grassiness mellows into elegant complexity, while acidity remains the wine's structural foundation.</p>

<h3>Optimal Storage Conditions</h3>

<p>Store bottles at <strong>50-55°F with 70% humidity</strong>, lying horizontally away from light. Unlike reds, Sauvignon Blanc's delicate aromatics suffer quickly from temperature fluctuations above 60°F.</p>

<h3>Peak Drinking Windows</h3>

<ul>
<li><strong>Entry-level wines</strong>: Within 18 months of vintage</li>
<li><strong>Premium single-vineyard bottlings</strong>: 2-5 years</li>
<li><strong>Top Loire examples</strong>: 5-12 years</li>
<li><strong>Bordeaux Blanc blends</strong>: 8-15 years</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Signs of proper aging</strong> include developing golden hues and integrated aromatics, while spoilage shows as flat acidity, oxidized honey notes, or loss of varietal character entirely.</p>

